He was not only a poet but a poet- laureate. It is the poet who pens the speeches> of Dido, while the poet-laureate describes the ‘good Aeneas' to gratify a prince who in order to found an empire—dum conderet urbem—would certainly not have let a woman's ruin stand in the way of state policy or his own ambition.

Although, however, as an epic poem the Aeneid is wanting in vitality and human interest, the praise of eighteen centuries is sufficient evidence of its striking merits. What those merits are has been already partly indicated in referring to the GeorgiCS. Virgil is a master of melodious rhythm‚ and he is a master of literary expression. The Latin hexameter, which in Ennius, the father of Latin poetry‚ is cumbrous and uncouth‚ and in Lucretius, though powerful and impos- ing, still lacks grace and versatility‚ has been moulded by Virgil into a perfect instrument capable of infinite varieties and responsive to every phase of emotion3 while as regards his literary power it is impossible to read ten lines anywhere without coming across one of those felicitous phrases the charm of which is beyond question as it is beyond analysiS. But these external graces are not all. Virgil is a man of deep though controlled feeling.
